  "response_text": "**16-Week Beginner Marathon Training Schedule**\n\nThis schedule is designed for a beginner runner who has some experience with running, but is new to marathon training. It's essential to start with a solid foundation of regular running and gradually increase the mileage and intensity over time.\n\n**Weeks 1-4: Building a Base (Weeks 1-4)**\n\n* Goal: Establish a regular running routine, 3 times a week, with one longer run on the weekends\n* Workouts:\n\t+ Monday: 30-minute easy run (3 miles)\n\t+ Wednesday: 30-minute easy run (3 miles)\n\t+ Saturday: 45-minute easy run (4-5 miles)\n\t+ Sunday: Rest day or cross-training (e.g., walking, cycling, or swimming)\n* Gradually increase weekly mileage by 10% each week\n\n**Weeks 5-8: Building Endurance (Weeks 5-8)**\n\n* Goal: Increase weekly mileage, introduce speed workouts, and incorporate rest days\n* Workouts:\n\t+ Monday: 30-minute easy run (3 miles)\n\t+ Tuesday: 30-minute speed workout (intervals, hill repeats, or tempo runs)\n\t+ Thursday: 30-minute easy run (3 miles)\n\t+ Saturday: 60-minute easy run (6-7 miles)\n\t+ Sunday: Rest day or cross-training\n* Introduce strength training (1-2 times a week) to target core, glutes, and legs\n\n**Weeks 9-12: Building Distance (Weeks 9-12)**\n\n* Goal: Increase longest run of the week, introduce longer runs on weekends, and continue speed workouts\n* Workouts:\n\t+ Monday: 30-minute easy run (3 miles)\n\t+ Tuesday: 30-minute speed workout\n\t+ Thursday: 30-minute easy run (3 miles)\n\t+ Saturday: 75-minute easy run (8-9 miles)\n\t+ Sunday: Rest day or cross-training\n* Gradually increase weekly mileage by 10% each week\n* Continue strength training (1-2 times a week)\n\n**Weeks 13-16: Taper and Rest (Weeks 13-16)**\n\n* Goal: Reduce weekly mileage, focus on active recovery, and prepare for the marathon\n* Workouts:\n\t+ Monday: 30-minute easy run (3 miles)\n\t+ Tuesday: 30-minute easy run (3 miles)\n\t+ Thursday: 30-minute easy run (3 miles)\n\t+ Saturday: 60-minute easy run (6-7 miles)\n\t+ Sunday: Rest day or cross-training\n* Reduce weekly mileage by 20-30% each week\n* Focus on rest, recovery, and visualization techniques\n\n**Additional Tips**\n\n1. **Listen to your body**: Rest and recovery are crucial. If you experience any discomfort or pain, take an extra day off or modify your workout.\n2. **Stay hydrated**: Drink plenty of water throughout the day, and aim to consume 16-20 ounces of fluid 1-2 hours before each run.\n3. **Fuel your body**: Eat a balanced diet that includes complex carbohydrates, lean protein, and healthy fats.\n4. **Get enough sleep**: Aim for 7-9 hours of sleep each night to aid in recovery and performance.\n5. **Find a running buddy or join a running group**: Running with others can help with motivation and accountability.\n\n**Remember**\n\n* This is a general training schedule, and it's essential to consult with a medical professional or a certified running coach to create a personalized plan.\n* Be patient and consistent, and don't be afraid to adjust the schedule as needed.\n* Most importantly, have fun and enjoy the journey to your first marathon finish!",
